      <hedline>
        <hl1>One That Got Away</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>William Manning letter on Ann Wilson Lloyd's August 6 article calls destruction of Frederick Law Olmsted's Wood Island Park in East Boston a tragedy (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ann Wilson Lloyd's article on the artists whose work commemorates and comments on Frederick Law Olmsted's park system in Boston [''Remembering Olmsted's Vision for Boston,'' Aug. 6] was a welcome spotlight on the treasure we have in his ''Emerald Necklace'' that meanders through the city.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Ann Wilson Lloyd's article on the artists whose work commemorates and comments on Frederick Law Olmsted's park system in Boston [''Remembering Olmsted's Vision for Boston,'' Aug. 6] was a welcome spotlight on the treasure we have in his ''Emerald Necklace'' that meanders through the city.</p>
        <p>A tragedy that I wish someone had commemorated, however, was the destruction of Olmsted's Wood Island Park, a 70-acre waterfront park in East Boston that was the last, northernmost jewel in that necklace. It was the glory of East Boston, a working-class neighborhood with few public amenities, and was ranked with San Francisco's Golden Gate Park as one of the country's great oceanside municipal parklands. It now sits under a runway at Logan Airport, bulldozed in the 1960's by a state agency that put planes ahead of local residents and a great landscape legacy.</p>
        <p>WILLIAM MANNING  Boston</p>
        <p>OLMSTED AND BOSTON</p>
      </block>
